Announces a competition for grass mowing in lanes of road compartments.
The Latvian road maintainer of VAS has announced a procurement for mechanized lawn mowing in the road compartment lanes in the regions of Latvia and in Pierīga, informs LAU.
The object of the procurement is divided into 9 lots: Alūksnes, Daugavpils, Jēkabpils, Jelgava, Rēzekne, Valmiera, Talsi and Riga Road Districts.
Tenderers may submit a tender for one or more lots.
Mowing of grass in the lanes of road compartments is necessary to improve the transparency of roads and areas adjacent to them by drivers, to facilitate the delivery of water from the road, and to limit grassing and threshing.
The most ambitious lawn mowing works are planned for farmers in Talsi road district for a total of 637 hiking kilometres on 28 roads, in Valmiera road district for 20 roads for 432 hiking kilometres, and in Aluksne for 17 roads for 384 hiking kilometres.
It has already been reported that in June the company completed the lawn mowing work on the main and most important regional asphalt roads of the country, but on smaller regional roads and on local roads the maintainer of the Latvian motorways of the VAS planned to entrust the mowing work to farmers.
"It is an opportunity for us to use the funding allocated to road maintenance works more efficiently, while at the same time allowing farmers to fully load the machinery and earn", emphasizes Vladimirs Kononovs, Chairman of the Board of SJSC Latvian Road Maintainer.
The deadline for the submission of tenders is 22 August.
Ombudsman: Demagogy on the model of compulsory health insurance with an additional financial burden on citizens does not hold any criticism.
Any demagoguery on compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and increased burden of payment on residents, does not hold any criticism, according to Ombudsman Juris Jansons.
Jansons met today with Health Minister Anda Čakša to discuss the situation in the health sector.
After the meeting, Jansons told journalists that the sector funding model proposed by the Minister of Health was sustainable and would develop the healthcare system, making it more accessible to patients.
He noted, however, that in this case, additional funding for health care should be discussed, as it is currently insufficient.
Jansons also stressed that any demagogy on compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and increased burden of payment on the population, did not hold any criticism, especially when the Dutch model is invoked.
Jansons said that the Netherlands allocates 11% of gross domestic product to health, while Latvia - only 3%.
So the government and parliament must be responsible enough to understand that from this freezing point, the Ombudsman said that otherwise the model proposed by the Ministry of Health (VM) would not work.
Čaksha thanked the Ombudsman for his support and pointed out that the main concern is that the patient should get a doctor, which in turn means that the health care system needs additional funding.
The Minister pointed out, however, that with an additional EUR 35 million planned, it will be possible to do only the most acute things next year regarding oncological patients and remuneration of maternity specialists.
As a result, the MFA has developed a plan and submitted a request for an additional €41 million to be allocated to health care in order to reduce queues with specialists and for examinations.
"A question of priorities, whether it will have the means or not", said Chaksha.
However, this amount does not include an increase in remuneration for medical practitioners.
Commenting on the fact that the medics are not enthusiastic about directing all three variants of the healthcare funding model, including one that provides for an additional payment to patients, to the HM for consideration in the government, Chaksha said that directing all three models gives the government the opportunity to choose.
Jansons also added that by directing all three models, it is possible to show clearly that Latvia is not ready to impose an additional burden on the population.
It has already been reported that the MoU will defend the variant of the healthcare financing model, which does not foresee an increase in the overall tax burden, but requires a part of the social tax to be directed towards health, says the conceptual summary of the report "On the change of the financing model of the Latvian health care system".
At the same time, the Ministry indicated that the best variant of the model for financing health care will be chosen as a result of discussions by the end of September.
