How to prepare for a family photo shoot.
The summer is still in full swing, as is immediately the next school year, which families can capture in photo memory.
To make the pictures look happy and beautiful, it is worth considering how to prepare for the photo shoot in advance.
Advice "Ihappymama" is provided by many children's mom Alexandra Nesterenko and professional photographer Marina Levickaya.
You have to take pictures in nature, because it is much more natural and harmonious.
It is much more difficult for children to get involved and relax during their studies.
It is recommended to choose a uniform style of dress for the whole family, preferably in the same range of colors.
For example, Alexandra says that she chooses clothing for all six family members so that the clothes are in no more than three shades of color and as few inscriptions as possible on the clothing.
Don't forget the good mood.
Have fun, joke, play, but do not scream or psyche if the children are not as obedient as they would like.
And here’s the next advice from a professional photographer’s dowry box!
You have to understand exactly what you want to capture during the photo shoot and tell the photographer about it.
For some, they will be beautiful, accurate children and an ideal family picture, for others, "life is what it is like", namely, the desire to see real, true emotions in the pictures, or, as the photographer himself loves to say, "refugees in the backs", "faced with eyes", "torn up the nose".
Of course, it happens that someone wants "two in one" as well, but it rarely happens.
In any case, when you go to a photo shoot, you have to understand that it's just a couple of hours from your life, and the less you'll be stuck, the better.
Be yourself - there's no rigid mom who works, cooks, raises and so on, and not the always busy dad who's constantly talking on the phone.
And neither is the man who lives in you behind some unknown shell.
Be a family, remember how great it is to hug each other, smile at your own and make fun of yourself.
And then the photographer's job will be to capture the real moments of the emotions that prevail between you.
If you have chosen a photographer, trust him.
Stop asking 250 times to show what's happened, listen to his advice on choosing clothing, a place for better shots.
Bend and iron all the clothes in advance, so that the day of the photo shoot no longer needs to be dealt with.
Plan the route and think about how long it will take for you to get to the photo shoot (especially if the photo is in the studio and the time is limited).
If you have young children, choose the time for the photo shoot that corresponds to the day of the offspring so that it does not happen at the time the baby normally sleeps.
And, of course, don't forget to bring food, cookies, water and a favorite toy with your children (to be used only in extreme situations).
While preparing his dad that he may have to take his socks off, she doesn’t usually write about it in such articles, and only the photographers know what the problem is, says Marina.
Don't drink much water before the photo shoot and get a good sleep before.
And it would be advisable to have some entertainment together after the photo shoot.
Go to the amusement park, eat some ice cream, take a ride with roller skates - which the family likes more.
This way you will have at the same time acquired great pictures and pleasant memories of the day you spent together.
Krasnopjorov and Fadejeva: Raising the minimum wage - a miracle boom or a brake for the economy?
The issue of raising the minimum wage in public debate has almost the status of a sacred cow: either promotion should be supported or there should be mentioned some non-spoken, general phrases.
Taking into account the significant increase in the risk of stagnation of the economy (just barely avoided technical recession), we believe it is important to stress that raising the minimum wage is not a miracle that will reduce income inequality with one hint, will bring Latvian wages closer to the level of Western Europe and will fill the state budget.
On the contrary, if the minimum wage is raised too much, it does more harm than good, because it undermines the competitiveness and employment of businesses, especially in low-income sectors and regions.
At first sight, it seems that, despite several increases in the minimum wages in the post-crisis period, the minimum wage in Latvia is not so high that raising by the usual few tens of euros a year would significantly weaken the competitiveness of businesses - only 370 euros, while in some European Union (EU) countries the minimum wage is around one and a half thousand.
However, a different picture can be seen if we compare it with the average wage in the country (%) - the minimum wage in Latvia (44%) exceeds the EU average.
Since Latvia has a significantly higher share of the minimum wage recipients than neighbouring countries (17% in Latvia, 11% in Lithuania, 6% in Estonia[1]), a similar increase in the minimum wage is binding for most companies.
According to the results of the survey of Latvijas Banka companies, one in five Latvian companies replied that, as the minimum wage increased at the beginning of 2014, it was important or very important for it to increase the prices of products.
This means, firstly, that the rise in the minimum wage was partly financed by consumers (i.e. residents of Latvia); secondly, the increase in prices for several companies meant a loss of competitiveness both in the domestic market and abroad (i.e., increased imports and limited exports).
Due to weaker competitiveness and shrinking production volumes, it was important for almost one in fifteen Latvian companies to lay off employees (which means more unemployment and emigration).
In addition, almost one in eleven companies responded that it was important for him to limit the recruitment of new employees as a result of raising the minimum wage.
It is worth remembering that in 2011 - 2013 the minimum wage in Latvia did not change.
Therefore, even if one in five companies considered the improvement of productivity to be important when assessing the 2014 minimum wage increase, this does not mean that a similar result could be expected in 2017 (the fourth consecutive increase of the minimum wage could exhaust the possibilities of increasing productivity).
Another important result is that, due to the rise in the minimum wage, it was also important for several companies to increase the remuneration of employees earning more than the minimum wage.
Thus, the impact of the minimum wage was significant even for companies where none of the employees received the minimum wage.
In recent years, the rise in the minimum wage in all three Baltic States exceeded the increase in nominal labour productivity (real labour productivity + inflation).
Thus, a further increase in the minimum wage, despite the overall rather low level in euro, will have a negative impact on the competitiveness and employment of enterprises.
When assessing the validity of raising the minimum wage, an analysis of the economic average is not enough.
It is also necessary to assess whether raising minimum wages is "surmountable" in sectors and regions where minimum wages are most commonly used.
The results of the Bank of Latvia survey show that the greatest concentration of employees with minimum wages is in small enterprises (the number of employees is from 10 to 19 employees; 25%).
At the end of 2013, the share of employees in the industrial and service sectors with minimum wages was higher (respectively 16% and 19%) than in trade (15%), construction (11%) and financial and insurance (2%).
On the other hand, for Latgale, where the minimum wage is 64% of the average wage (and more than two thirds of the average wage in the private sector), its further rise may be more detrimental by reducing labour demand (i.e., maintaining already high unemployment) and contributing to the sustainability of the shadow economy.
Some signs indicate that the substantial rises in the minimum wage (by 27% in total) implemented in 2014 - 2015 have slowed the development of Latgale.
For example, Latgale is the only region of Latvia where unemployment was higher in 2015 than in 2013.
It should be noted that Estonia and Lithuania do not have any regions that fall so far behind in terms of average wages from the rest of the country.
In Estonia, for example, the average wage in all regions is at least twice the national minimum wage.
Lithuania has the lowest wages in the Tauraģe region, but there too the minimum wage in 2015 was 54% of the average wage (after two rapid minimum wage increases in 2016 this indicator could reach 58%).
The public debate has occasionally called for the minimum wage to be raised to 68% of the average wage in the country (see, for example, here) lacks economic justification and cannot be achieved in the short or long term.
Firstly, such a high figure of the average wage, or even as close to it, is not present in any EU country.
Secondly, it would mean raising the minimum wage above the average wage in several branches of the economy (which would mean bankruptcy and mass redundancies of companies in these branches), for example, in the production of clothing, leather products, fish processing, catering services, as well as veterinary services; moreover, it is more than the current average wage in the private sector of Latgale.
Raising the minimum wage from January 2017 to 400-410 euros per month, as currently offered by the Ministry of Welfare, would make the minimum wage in Latvia (% of the average wage) one of the highest in the EU.
If nominal productivity increases by 4% and the minimum wage is at least twice as fast, this has clearly negative consequences for business competitiveness and employment.
Such negative consequences will be most prevalent in those sectors and regions where the current minimum wage level is often used, for example, in Latgale.
The fact that a significant increase in the minimum wage is currently unaffordable means that other mechanisms must be applied to support low wage earners.
An immediate effect can be achieved by travelling with a tax-exempt minimum (within the limits of the budget) of personal income tax.
Insufficient levels of education, inadequate education and poor quality of education, and poor health (which often occurs without recourse to a doctor due to the cost of medical services and long queues) are among the real causes of income inequality.
During the survey 521 responses were obtained from the Latvian company regarding the response to the rise in the minimum wage in January 2014.
The survey was conducted as part of the Wage Dynamics Network (WDN) project.
These figures represent companies with a number of employees of not less than 10.
This also explains the low proportion of workers with minimum wages in construction.
