Policemen rescue the infant from overheating in the car; parents for knocking out glass threaten court actions.
In Riga yesterday municipal policemen rescued the infant from a hot car, while the child's parents threatened police officers with court proceedings about the broken glass of the car, the agency LETA informed the Riga Municipal Police (RPP).
Yesterday, an upset man ran up to the patrol, who told him that he noticed a car in the shopping centre's Spice parking lot, where an infant is present for half an hour without the presence of adults.
When arriving at the scene, an eyewitness's designated car was looked up, which was parked in the sun.
The front passenger seat had a child seat containing the infant.
It was the rays of the sun that shone on the child.
The infant shouted loudly, breathed intensely, and his face was reddened and sweaty.
Given that the owner of the vehicle was not on site, an immediate decision has been made to knock out the rear glass of the car in order not to endanger the health and life of the infant.
The child with the entire seat highlighted from the hot vehicle, and called medics.
The child breathed shallow, the skin was reddened and hot, so by the time medical doctors arrived, the caretakers put a cool compression on their forehead.
Medical and child's parents arrived almost simultaneously at the scene.
The infant's father, upon seeing the broken window for his vehicle, remained aggressive and the medics were not allowed to the child.
Discussions with parents and it is explained that children under the age of seven are forbidden to leave one unattended.
In addition, the child was left behind in life - threatening conditions.
After the discussion, medical doctors looked at the victim and found that there was no need for hospitalization.
The child’s parents, on the other hand, categorically refused to give any explanation about what had happened and threatened court proceedings about the broken glass of the car.
During the discussions with their parents, there was no evidence that they were under the influence of alcohol or could harm their child in any other way, so the baby, less than four months old, was taken into the care of the two.
Case materials have been sent to the Division for Prevention of Offences in Children, whose employees will assess parental responsibility.
The RMP reminds us that even if the outside is not very hot, a car left in the sun heats up very quickly.
