In Thailand, four people died in bomb blasts in tourist attractions
After the Thai people voted to adopt the Constitution, there were a series of bomb blasts on Thursday and Friday in five southern provinces of Thailand - popular tourist destinations - in which four died and many people were injured.
The first two explosions threw off at a seaside resort in Huahin on Thursday evening, the next - Friday morning.
The town is about 200 kilometers south of Bangkok.
Police stated that one Thai woman was killed in the first explosion and 20 people were injured, 10 of them foreigners.
Authorities confirmed that other explosions slumped the southern cities of Phooket, Trana, and Suratthani.
Two bombs exploded in the suburb of Phuketa in Patonga and two more in Phanna Province - a tourist region north of Phuketa.
There have been 11 bomb blasts in Thailand in the past 24 hours.
On Friday, a Thai Royal Police official, Colonel Chrisana Patanacharoen, stated that the blasts were unrelated to Islamic extremists and were considered local acts of sabotage.
"It is still too early to draw conclusions," he said.
"But we absolutely know that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact it's local sabotage, and we're trying to find the perpetrators."
After a small power bomb explosion in Huachin on August 12, 2016, investigators collected evidence from the crime scene.
On 12 August, officials announced that four people had been killed in a series of bomb blasts in Thailand's important tourist areas. Competent authorities are trying to determine the motive and find the perpetrators.
There are no conflicts in the country that could cause terrorists to be in the country.
"So we can say these incidents are not terrorist attacks," he continued.
No group has yet assumed responsibility for the attack, and the competent authorities have not charged any specific groups, but the explosions occurred the same week that Thai voters approved the new Constitution.
All three southern provinces - Huahina, Phuketa and Phanna - rejected the military-backed referendum, and in the southeastern provinces of Thailand, where the majority of the population are Muslims, more than 6,500 people have died in the riots since 2004.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of Queen Sirikita of Thailand, which is a national holiday in Thailand.
Huachin is home to the royal palace of Klai Kangwon, or "the castle far from the worries", in which the Thai royal family often tends to reside.
King Bumibol Adulyadei was the longest reigning monarch in the world.
