Signs of unrest in Ukraine make you ask the question: What is Vladimir Putin thinking?
It has become apparent that these claims are true.
Ukraine denies them, while the US and the European Union claim that Russia has not provided any evidence.
The open analysis group, the Digital Forensic Research Lab, has found some signs of Saturday shooting, but quite little to be able to hinder Moscow's major plans.
Russia is known for distorting or misinterpreting events for political purposes, especially in the context of the ongoing conflict in Ukraine.
This does not mean that all Russian claims are unfounded.
Members of the Ukrainian resistance forces damaged last year the electricity pylons supplying the current to Crimea, some of which are also involved in criminal activities and human rights violations.
The attempted attack in Crimea is still a topical issue, although there is little reason to suspect that the Ukrainian government would sponsor a scenario of such events.
Whatever happened, images found by open source analysts show that Russia has been increasing its military presence ever since at least last Saturday - before the anticipated attack took place.
They show heavy-arm convoys moving along the peninsula, including missile systems designed to protect the coast.
Disturbingly Known Escalation of Russia
Separate reports indicate that the Russian forces in Crimea had already planned rotation around this time, which could help explain the activity, although it would be a very coincidence that it just happened to happen in one of the fullest times of tension since the annexation in 2014.
Whatever has become known over the weekend, Mr Putin has undoubtedly turned to Ukraine even more in his statements, choosing to use this episode, however real it may be, for what greater purpose.
Analysts point to worrying parallels with Russia's treatment just before previous military actions against Ukraine.
In February 2014, similar speeches and military manoeuvres provided a cover for the Crimean volunteer members of the resistance force to occupy the peninsula, which was still controlled by Ukraine at the time, only to reveal that in fact they were Russian special units that initiated the military occupation.
In August, when Russian-backed separatists failed in Eastern Ukraine, Putin deployed forces along the border, warning that they might be needed for the "protection" of ethnic Russian civilians in Ukraine who are being attacked according to him.
He arranged a relief convoy to the region, which according to NATO was only a cover-up of Russian invasion forces.
What does Mr. Putin intend to do in Crimea?
Some have guessed whether only Moscow is planning another military intervention.
The fighting in Eastern Ukraine has escalated, as it was before the invasion in August 2014.
But this supposed parallel could be the point when it is intended to introduce a fear of military action, not of actual action, - this will give Putin a trump card, both in his relations with Ukraine and with Western countries.
Mark Galeoti, a professor at the University of Nuyork who studies Russia, pointed out that Crimea would have little meaning as the point from which to start military actions against Eastern Ukraine, which borders the land part of Russia rather than the Crimea, and that the rest of the country is better protected.
"There's a pretty little chance if the Russians really are planning some large-scale offensive", Mr Galeoti said.
Rather, "we can observe a classic Russian strategy of creating a pressure."
International peace talks on Ukraine, once a mechanism with which Putin imposed contacts with Western leaders who ignored him due to the annexation of Crimea, are increasingly seen by more and more people as unsuccessful and irrelevant.
By promising that there is a danger that the conflict may flare up again, Putin gives a new meaning to the negotiations: to get him off the edge of the abyss.
"It's standard Putin's tactics - he wants to try to start from a position of strength," Galeoti said of the next peace talks scheduled for early September.
"And the only strong point is to say, 'If I wanted to, I could make everything even much, much worse.'"
Reaching an agreement with the West
Putin also said this week that during the Crimean tensions there was little point in continuing the negotiations, forcing other parties to convince him to return to the negotiating table and to come to the centre of the process.
What does it actually give him?
Firstly, it allows Russia to continue to establish itself as a world power, although its economy is smaller than that of Australia.
Secondly, it positions Moscow as having the right of veto over the sovereignty of Ukraine, keeping the country under Russian control to some extent.
It may also benefit Putin's long-held hopes of a large-scale agreement with the United States, which would resolve their disputes on the issue of Ukraine and Syria, on favourable terms for Moscow, naturally, also ending Western sanctions against Russia.
Putin has hinted at this goal since the country's economic deterioration in 2014, has been made several times, mainly due to the country's declining value of its oil and gas exports.
Since his invasion of Syria last autumn, he has repeatedly called on the Western powers to join him in the great coalition to fight extremists.
However, Russian leaders may believe that they would need to secure such an agreement before January, when President Obama's term expires.
Russian officials basically believe that the next president will be Hillary Clinton, who is more hostile to Moscow.
Donald J. Trump, although noticeably friendly to Russia, is still considered unpredictable.
Obama, on the other hand, is considered to be one who "searches for solutions rather than conflicts," Galeoti said.
So it makes sense to close the window of opportunity to get something done quickly.
Meanwhile, if a large-scale agreement is not reached, it seems that Putin is satisfied with keeping Russia's weak neighbour by citing what will be next.
An earlier version of this article misstated the year that Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine.
This was in 2014, not in 2013.
As Congress enters a dead end, the White House directs funds to fight Zika virus
The Obama administration said on Thursday that it would divert US$81 million from biomedical research and anti-poverty and health care programs to pay for the development of a vaccine against the Zika virus, resorting to emergency measures as Congress did not approve new funding to combat the virus.
Sylvia Matthews Barwell , Secretary of Health and Humanities, in a letter to members of Congress, indicated that without the funds diverted, the National Institute of Health and the Biomedical In-Depth Research and Development Authority would remain without money to fight mosquito-borne disease until the end of the month.
Therefore, the vaccine would have to be discontinued at an important moment as the number of Zika disease cases acquired in the country increases in Miami.
Last week, there were 7,350 cases of Zika virus reported in the United States, mostly in Puerto Rico (according to Centers for Disease Control and Prevention).
Mrs. Barwell said that 15 babies were born to birth defects related to Zika virus.
The virus can cause brain development abnormalities and other severe defects in children born to infected mothers.
The prevalence of the disease in the continental United States, when the first cases were recorded at the end of last month, has raised political rates into a federal government response.
Hillary Clinton stopped in Wainwood, a neighborhood in Miami on Tuesday as part of the campaign, which saw an outbreak of locally transmitted Zika virus cases, and put pressure on Congress to return from its five-week break to confirm emergency funding to fight the virus.
President Obama and Congressional Republicans have been in conflicting thoughts for most of the year on Zika virus issues.
Obama claimed US$1.9 billion in emergency funding in February.
The Republicans stopped this by demanding a more detailed account of what the money would be spent on.
Lawmakers have been arguing for months about how much money should be allocated and how it should be spent.
Last month, Democrats blocked consideration of the measure proposed by Republicans when they would allocate US$1.1 billion to fight Zika virus , but would include provisions that would prohibit the allocation of funds for family planning to provide contraceptives for a virus that can be so transmitted through the sex route.
Because of this impasse, the White House in April was forced to divert $589 million to fight against the Ebola virus, the Zika virus. About two-thirds of the funding is to be used within the country.
On Thursday, Mrs. Barwell said that her department had spent most of the money and that it would be spent in full by the end of August.
"The failure to make a decision on emergency funding for the fight against Zika virus has led the administration to choose between postponing the work of developing the important vaccine and catching up with other valuable national programs to temporarily avoid this postponement," Barvela wrote.
Democrats clung to this statement to accuse Republicans of not giving extra money to fight Zika virus.
At the news conference, spokeswoman Nancy Pelosi of California, a minority leader, invited Representative Paul D.Ryan, Speaker of the House of Representatives, to remind Congress of moving this event forward.
"All the opportunities are exhausted and now we turn to the National Institute of Health," Ms Pelosi said.
Mr. Ryan's advisers say that channeling funds is a step that had to be taken a long time ago and has been delayed by the Obama administration in order to extort maximum political benefit from the Zika virus problem.
Last week, the National Institute of Health announced that it had started clinical trials of the vaccine against Zika virus with 80 people, and hopes to start a second phase in the "Zika virus epidemic countries" in early 2017.
However, as officials claimed on Thursday, without immediate additional funding, the study will stop.
Barwell said she would divert US$34 million from the National Health Service funds for the search for cures for other diseases, including cancer and diabetes, to fight Zika virus.
A further 47 million will be transferred to the Biomedical in-depth research and development facility supporting the development of medicines and vaccines in response to public health emergencies.
