And today, young girls can target a number of existing role models, operating in the highest field of leadership.
So, is the long and hard fight for women's equality really over at last?
Hillary Clinton is ready to become President of the United States at any time, however, in the field of religion, female leadership remains a controversial issue.
Okay, not completely.
In the religious field, female leadership remains a contentious issue.
Last week, Pope Francis announced the creation of a new commission with the aim of assessing whether women should be consecrated as deacons in the Catholic Church.
The Anglican Church consecrated Libya Lane as the first woman-bishop in January 2015, but this was only after a failed attempt in 2012.
While women have been ordained in the reform Jewish movement since the early 1970s and the conservative movement since the early 1980s, in orthodox Judaism, the concept of female rabbi still has a very fierce resistance.
In November 2015, the American Board of Orthodox Rabbis published a rather harsh message in its third attempt to stem the ever-increasing wave of support for the rabbinic prescription of Orthodox women that the concept of female-rabbi is contrary to the law.
Not without irony when Hillary Clinton was nominated as a Democratic presidential candidate, a group of American leading Orthodox rabbis who oppose the ordination of women launched a series of "discussions" on this controversial issue.
Why is there a difference between secular and sacral?
Orthodox Judaism, like most other religions, seeks stability in what it sees as enduring traditional values.
It manifests itself in being able to resist pressure to adapt to a changing society.
Those who are against female ordination do so on the grounds that it is not "traditional."
However, overwhelming with the preservation of traditions in this way has its price.
And the price of such one-sided thinking can paradoxically undermine tradition in its own right by depriving the traditional community of the oxygen it needs to maintain vitality.
In the book "August Guns", in the military history of the First World War, Barbara Tachman emphasizes the danger of giving priority to the tradition in what has become known as the "tragedy of red trousers."
Until the outbreak of the First World War, when warfare moved from warfare over close distances to heavier artillery being transmitted from a further distance, it became advantageous to hide the soldiers as long as possible.
The British and German armies responded to these changes by replacing their bright uniforms with boring greys and browns.
French soldiers, however, still wore the same red hats and pants, which made them light targets.
The proposal by the French Minister of War Affairs, Adolf Messimí, that the armies under his command could act similarly, was perceived with ridicule and resistance.
The red pants reflected the pride and prestige of the army, and the military traditionalists were not prepared to abandon it.
Speaking in parliament, former Minister of War Affairs Eugene Etienne spoke on behalf of France.
"Abandoning the red pants?" he exclaimed.
Never!
"It's the unspeakable and idiotic appendix to the most obvious of all colors," Messimee then wrote, "had to have evil consequences."
Faith leaders who fight to include women in leading religious roles could fall into the same trap.
Focusing solely on the "traditional" religion, not asking the important question, "What change is needed for religion to flourish?" they risk losing about 50 percent of their followers.
They also take away from the whole community the talent, skills and enthusiasm that women would otherwise provide.
To insist that men continue to wear pants when it comes to religion may be traditional, but as the destruction of red trousers suggests, it may not be worth it.
Dina Breiver is a founding member of the JOFA (Women's Orthodox Feminist Association) in Britain and a student of orthodox rabbinism at the Yeshivath Maharat in New York City.
