Lurda prepares to welcome pilgrims in the shadow of attacks
People gather at the shrine of Our Lady of Lurd during the annual Catholic pilgrimage.
French security forces are in high alert readiness as thousands of Catholics gather at the Shrine of Lurd on an annual pilgrimage in the shadow of several acts of terror.
Each year on August 15, tens of thousands of people gather at the shrine at the foot of the Pyrenees Mountains to celebrate the Ascension Festival to celebrate the reception of the virgin Mary in heaven.
This year's pilgrimage comes at a time when Catholics are shocked by the killing of an elderly French priest on 26 July by two Islamic extremists who invaded the church in northern France during Mass and cut his throat.
The murder of Jacques Amel took place two weeks after a Tunisian -- investigators say he was radicalized by the Jihadist online footage -- crashed into a truck in a Bastille Day celebration crowd in the city of Riviera, Nice, killing 85 people.
After three large-scale attacks in 18 months, many French people are cautious about attending public events.
The number of tourists declined dramatically, and the authorities feared that the number of pilgrims this year could plummet.
However, fear of mass withdrawals did not materialize -- and some organizers say there has been even an influx of visitors' applications at the last minute.
The arrival of some 25 000 believers is expected, including large groups from Italy and Belgium and a delegation of approximately 200 Orthodox representatives from the Eastern branch of Christianity.
Many pilgrims have stated that they will not be intimidated.
"We don't mean to stop living," a 66-year-old visitor, Christian, told AFP agency, describing prayer as "the only weapon" in the fight against violence.
"It's important to show that life continues," said Matier Guinar - one of the coordinators.
We will not give up our faith, our beliefs, and our way of life just because some fanatics are trying to sow fear.
Due to security concerns in France, several large-scale events have been cancelled since the attack in Nice, including a huge stock market in the northern city of Lille and the European Cycling Championships on the highway, which was to take place in Nice in September.
"Last week, I live in fear that my phone will call in one call to withdraw applications," Fabien Ležesne said last weekend - the priest in charge of the official pilgrimage process.
"On the contrary - it seems that the attacks have mobilized believers," he said and announced the influx of last-minute applications.
The head of the local hotel workers' trade association, Christian Göll, confirmed "an increased interest" in pilgrimage following the attacks.
Around the holy place where the virgin Mary was said to have appeared in the grotto in 1858 to a poor shepherd, Bernadette Subirou, there were extremely strict security measures set.
Approximately 250 police officers and two dozen soldiers have been assigned to protect the site, including bomb neutralization experts and experts with explosive search dogs.
As pilgrims thronged through security barriers, bags were checked at the entrance, with access points reduced from twelve to three.
Catherine Simcox, who traveled from northeast England on a pilgrimage to Lurd earlier this month, described the reinforced security measures.
"By Thursday morning, there were armed security guards in the shrines, and then through the gate (with metal barriers) only could enter one by one, as well as the bags were searched," she told The Local.
"This all frightened my three children, who are used to Lourda, and it was hard not to scare them when they asked why this was happening," she said.
It hasn't ruined my impressions, but I became sad at the fact that it was necessary, and I realized that many people were calmed down by these measures.
The route of Friday's opening procession has also been shortened - instead of starting in the city of Lurd and moving on to the shrine, it will begin and end in the shrine.
Other measures include closing airspace to flights over Lurd, closing streets near a traffic sanctuary, and replacing garbage bins for transparent plastic bags.
French Interior Minister Bernar Kazenev will test the security measures on Saturday.
About six million people travel to Lurda a year, making it one of the largest Catholic pilgrimage destinations in the world.
Many visitors lead relatives who are sick or disabled and who come to swim in a spring cave in which Bernadette reportedly saw Mary, believing in the healing properties of water.
Thierry Castijo, one of the organizers, described this year's gathering as "a little unusual", given the "threat as the roots seem to be in France."
However, he claimed that this would not affect the quality and depth of their experiences.
Françoise, a 58-old volunteer who helped sick pilgrims, admitted that, in her opinion, the presence of soldiers dressed in civilian clothing was "a little depressing."
However, if it soothes everyone, it's good.
