Waterfowl hunting takes place not only in hunting areas, but also in public water bodies, and although weather conditions do not promise heat like other years, it is permissible that these water bodies will be used by holidaymakers together with hunters.
We encourage hunters, holidaymakers and those living near water bodies to be particularly cautious about lakes and rivers and to comply with safety rules, thus not endangering themselves or others.
As in previous years it has been observed that during the first days of the season, a large number of hunters are involved in waterfowl hunting, the State Police in cooperation with the State Forest Service will also carry out reinforced hunting control this year.
Law enforcement officers during the control will pay attention to compliance of arms and ammunition movement with the norms of the law, as well as will monitor that the hunting process takes place without the influence of alcoholic beverages and intoxicating substances.
The police recall that the use of semi-automatic firearms with a total capacity of more than three patrons in waterfowl hunting is prohibited, including the attention to amendments to the Arms and Specialities Movement Act, in particular Article 22 (91), which states that persons with long firearms or large-energy pneumatic weapons registered for hunting or sport and during a short stop for up to two hours when they are being transported to or from hunting have the right to store the weapon and ammunition in the vehicle during the hunt, but must be placed in the safest place possible so that the case or other packaging containing the ammunition or weapon is not visible from the outside of the vehicle, is located behind locked doors and is equipped with an alarm device, thus ensuring that they do not accidentally enter into the hands of unauthorised persons.
Police call to take care of the safety of your and your fellow people during the hunting season, and if you see any violations or threats to security, we call 110 immediately.
In the event of any threat, law enforcement officers are ready to respond to the information provided by citizens.
The New Caledonian coast is shaken by a 7.2-magnitude earthquake
The New Caledonian coast was rocked by a 7.2-magnitude earthquake on Friday, reported by seismologists, indicating that there were no tsunami threats.
The epicenter of the earthquake was located at a depth of nine kilometers 109 kilometers east of New Caledonia, Ilantaire at 1.26 Greenwich time (at 4:26 p.m. Latvian time), stated the U.S. Geological Research Centre.
The Pacific Tsunami Alert Center indicated that there were no warnings or recommendations at this point in time regarding a possible tsunami threat to the region.
"The earthquakes in this region are not known to be unusual, nor are the activities unusual lately", said Phil Cummins, senior seismologist at the research center Geoscience Australia.
Potentially it could be felt in the Vanuatu or New Caledonian Islands, however, I doubt whether it is so strong as to cause damage.
New Caledonia is in the "Fire Circle" - a zone of Pacific tectonic activity where earthquakes and volcanic eruptions occur frequently.
Colombia and Venezuela agree to open the border.
Colombia and Venezuela agreed to open checkpoints on the border of the two countries, which closed on Venezuela's initiative a year ago, were told on Thursday by Colombian and Venezuelan presidents Juan Manuel Santos and Nicholas Maduro.
Initially, border posts will only be open to pedestrians.
From Saturday, five border posts will be open every day from 8 AM to 20 PM.
It will be possible to open the border to transport once certain international agreements on security, trade and energy have been concluded, said the Presidents.
Maduro ordered the border to be closed last August in response to an attack by Colombian militants on the Venezuelan border patrol.
Three Venezuelan soldiers were wounded in this attack.
In July this year, Venezuela unilaterally opened the border twice due to a sharp economic crisis - Venezuelans in poverty tried to break through the border to buy essential goods in border shops.
200,000 Venezuelan citizens took advantage of this opportunity.
