Turkey seeks out missing diplomats after coup attempt
Turkey is seeking at least 32 diplomats, who did not return with the staff withdrawn after the 15 July coup attempt.
Foreign Minister Mevits Chavušogls said on Friday that 208 Turkish ministry workers were withdrawn from jobs around the world for the duration of the coup attempt investigation to Ankara, and 32 have disappeared "without permission".
About 18,000 civilians, military leaders and academics have been arrested or withdrawn from their positions in Turkey, with the government considering them loyal to U.S. incumbent official Fetulla Gulen, whom it accuses of drafting a government overthrow plan.
Gulen, who lives in Pennsylvania, is on Turkey's list of the most wanted people.
Kavosoglu said that a team from the U.S. Department of Justice would come to Turkey later this month to discuss his possible extradition.
This issue has become a problem in US relations with Turkey, a member of NATO.
The U.S. opposed Turkish President Recep Tajjip Erdogan's strong-arms tactics after the coup, and Turkey responded by trying to establish closer ties with Russia.
Kavosoglu said that the Turkish military attachés in Greece had fled to Italy, the attaché in Kuwait attempted to escape to Saudi Arabia, but were sent back, and two generals from Afghanistan were caught in Dubai and sent to Turkey.
He also said that two officials in Bangladesh fled to New York, and one of Russia went to Japan.
The Ankara newspaper Daily Hurryiet, citing military sources, informed that the Turkish military attaché in Jordan was also missing.
The Wall Street Journal, citing a U.S. official who is aware of the situation, reported that a Turkish military officer based at the NATO command center in Virginia had requested asylum in the United States.
There are those who have managed to escape.
There have also been refugees among our diplomats," said NTV, a broadcaster, in an interview with Kavosoglu.
Since yesterday, time has run out for those who were originally withdrawn.
We will take legal action against those who did not return.
Olympic organizers are trying to clean the greenish hues of the diving pool
Olympic divers scheduled for training on Friday arrived at a closed pool as organizers needed more time to clear the water of greenish hues before the first individual competition at the Rio Olympics.
The water suddenly changed color on Tuesday, in the midst of synchronized diving competitions.
Organizers claimed that the water race was safe even after a larger adjacent pool for water polo and synchronized swimming, also stained lightly greenish.
Diving was not yet possible when athletes arrived for the morning warm-up, although finally the pool was opened at 13.00 local time - just 2 1/2 hours before the women's 3 metre race.
The color of the water looked closer to its usual color, yet still with a greenish hue.
American diver Abby Johnston, who competes on a tramp, told her that she came on a warm-up only to learn that the pool had been closed without any warning.
She wrote on Twitter that "#FixTheSwamp (correct the swamp) should be in fashion.
British diver Tom Daley, who won bronze in synchronized platform diving, also commented on the condition of the pool on Twitter.
Hopefully that means we haven't dived in as very bad in the last few days!
Mario Andrada, the chief spokesman of the local committee of organizers, stressed that the pool was safe for the race, giving the green light to the 3 metre preliminary races.
He agreed that water interfered with some athletes, however, he said that it was the result of the cleaning efforts of the pool.
"We repeat repeatedly what we have been saying all the time - water in no way endangers the health of athletes," he said.
On the first day of such a water situation, one or two athletes complained that they had itchy eyes.
It was the result that the first reaction, when we saw water turn green, was to use one of the chemicals - chlorine - it is used very often in swimming pools.
We reduced the amount immediately.
We checked the water again, and that was completely in line with the parameters.
Simon Langford, chief spokesman for the Mary Lenck Water Sports Center, said that the pool was closed for additional cleaning work.
He said that the decision was supported by the world's leading organization, FINA (International Swimming Federation).
"The reason is that the water must be calm so that the pool can get its blue paint again as soon as possible," Langford said in his statement.
Andrada said that the deterioration of the pool situation surprised the organizers unprepared.
"Chemistry is not an exact science," he said.
Some things, as you can see, lasted.
During the last few days, getting rainwater paint in normal condition made it even more difficult.
"Things don't work," Andrada said.
He added that athletes had access to dry workouts in the morning, however, he admitted that it "wasn't ideal."
He explained that the colour change in the basin was elevated due to alkalin levels, much like the water of the aquarium can become green if not properly monitored.
When we started doing something about green paint, there were discussions about the best chemicals.
We can't use too many chemicals in the water because athletes are training in it," Andrada said.
We could certainly have done better at the beginning to prevent the water from becoming green.
When it turned green, we made a mistake again.
AP sports reviewers Jay Cohen and Steve Wade took part in the making of this plot in Rio.
Shanghai, Taipei, despite stopping cross-border communication, however, will hold a forum
Shanghai and Taipei, however, will host the annual urban forum from August 22 to 23 in Taipei, announced by Shanghai Municipality on Friday, despite the suspension of cross-border communication mechanisms.
High-level municipal official Sha Hailin, on behalf of Shanghai Mayor Yang Xiong, will lead the delegation represented in the forum, announced by the Shanghai government on its official microblog account Sina Weibo.
Both cities have been holding the forum on a rotational basis since 2010.
The 2016 forum will focus on sharing experiences in areas such as health care, electronic administrative services, culture and transport, seeking to "in depth exchange of experiences and cooperation in different aspects" between the two cities, as reported by the Shanghai government.
The Taiwanese side has not recognised the agreement reached in 1992, which strengthened the one-China principle since the new leader Tsai Ing-ven took office in May, resulting in suspension of communication and consultation mechanisms.
Ma Ksiaoguangs , a state council spokesman for the Taiwan Office of Affairs on land, said Friday that peaceful cross-border relations may exist while the Taiwanese side adheres to the political foundations of the 1992 agreement.
"We have an active and open attitude towards the exchange of experiences between cities on both sides," said the MA stressing that the nature of cross-border relations and exchange of experiences between cities should be interpreted correctly.
Ugandan President meets China's foreign minister, hopes for closer cooperation
On Thursday, during a meeting with Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Ji, Ugandan President Joveri Museveni thanked China for its continued Ugandan development support and expressed his hope for closer cooperation.
Museveni said China was an old friend of Uganda and Africa who supported the African continent's liberation from colonialism and later supported Africa's economic and social development.
The President mentioned the construction of the Tanzania - Zambian railway in the 1970s as evidence of China's generous support, which was provided even when China itself was not very prosperous.
Museveni said that China had implemented multilateral cooperation with Uganda through both investment in infrastructure and business and cultural exchanges, and added that this kind of cooperation contributed to Uganda's long-term development more than just financial assistance.
He hopes that China will be able to engage in the development of Uganda's infrastructure and the construction of industrial parks in various ways.
He also invites the Chinese to invest more in and touring Uganda.
Wang Ji commended Uganda's work in the areas of industrialization and agricultural modernization and added that China would continue to be the most reliable and ideal cooperation partner of Uganda.
Wang stated that China was prepared to do everything possible to help implement Uganda's economic and social development, and added that China-Uganda cooperation was genuine and without any political considerations, as it was based on a high level of political credibility and time-tested friendship.
He said China could strengthen cooperation with Uganda in the construction of infrastructure and industrial parks, as well as supporting the development of the energy and agricultural industries of this East African nation.
